ationale |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **iPhone** | \u20b990,000 | 1 Year | **\u20b97,500** | **80% Ultra-Short Duration Fund**<br>**20% Low Duration Fund** | Maximizes safety for the core amount while a small allocation to slightly longer duration seeks better returns. |\n| **Bike** | \u20b9200,000 | 2 Years | **\u20b98,334** | **70% Banking & PSU Debt Fund**<br>**30% Corporate Bond Fund** | The 2-year horizon allows for taking slightly more credit and duration risk to earn higher, more stable returns than traditional FDs. |\n\n**C. Allocation for Surplus Beyond Goals**\n*   **Remaining Monthly Surplus:** \u20b934,000 - \u20b97,500 (iPhone) - \u20b98,334 (Bike) - (until Emergency Fund is built) = **~\u20b918,166**\n*   **This is where your \"Medium\" risk tolerance applies.**\n*   **Recommended Allocation:**\n    *   **50% Equity Mutual Funds (SIP):** A diversified index fund or a flexi-cap fund.\n    *   **25% Gold (SIP):** Via Gold ETF or Sovereign Gold Bond (SGB).\n    *   **15% Crypto:** *Only if you fully understand the risks.* Treat this as a speculative allocation. A small, fixed amount per month (e.g., \u20b92,500).\n    *   **10% Re-invest into Debt Bucket:** To further strengthen your low-risk portfolio.\n\n***\n\n### **5) Risks, Assumptions, and Mitigation**\n\n*   **Risks:**\n    *   **Interest Rate Risk:** If RBI raises rates, the NAV of your debt funds may see a temporary decline.\n    *   **Credit Risk (Mitigated):** The recommended fund categories (Banking & PSU, Corporate Bond) invest in highly rated instruments, minimizing default risk.\n    *   **Inflation Risk:** Returns may barely outpace inflation, but capital safety is the primary objective here.\n*   **Assumptions:**\n    *   Your income and expenses remain stable.\n    *   You do not have any other unforeseen major financial obligations.\n    *   You will not need to dip into these goal-specific investments prematurely.\n*   **Mitigation:**\n    *   **Stay the course.** 